ions of serious crimes perpetrated by its members, the last decade of the twentieth century was a tumultuous time for the Canadian Armed Forces. Amid this period, a human rights tribunal ordered the military to open its combat positions to women and reach full gender integration by 1999. Yet by 2021, women made up only 16.3 per cent of personnel; women and LGBTQ+ service members continue to face sexual harassment and abuse at all levels. In The Ones We Let Down Charlotte Duval-Lantoine looks at failed efforts to achieve gender parity during the 1990s. She reveals an organization unwilling and unable to change, and attitudes held by military leaders that fed a destructive dynamic and cost lives.As the military grapples with its failure to address cultural misconduct and change its culture, The Ones We Let Down reflects on whether the right lessons were learned from the decade of darkness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSexual harassment in the militaryzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen and the militaryzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh  aAct.  aAirborne Regiment.  aCharter.  aFreedom.  aHuman Rights Tribunal.  aOperation Honour.  aSomalia.  achain.  achange.  acombat arms.  acommand.  adecade darkness.  adiversity.  adoctrine.  adownsizing.  ahistory.  ainclusion.  amilitary.  aorganizational behaviour.  aprofession arms.  aservice members.  asexual misconduct.  atrust.  awarrior ethos.  awell being.  awomen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311127214608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022z978311127419540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022801271940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228012719423Co